Dialogue: 0,0:50:12.72,0:50:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,neurons within the brain. So that when\Nyou watch something happen your mind is
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.00,0:50:26.55,Default,,0,0,0,,also mirroring that and the neurons are\Nregistering it
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.55,0:50:30.16,Default,,0,0,0,,uh with a differentiation. There is a\Ndifferentiation in the neuron whether it
Dialogue: 0,0:50:30.16,0:50:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,actually happened or you just witnessed\Nit. But you can practice the thing. So
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.48,0:50:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,if you want to learn how to do\Nsomething, you don't have to actually go
Dialogue: 0,0:50:38.40,0:50:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,out and practice it. You can just\Nwitness it. And if you watch it enough
Dialogue: 0,0:50:41.68,0:50:48.96,Default,,0,0,0,,times, you can go step right on the\Ndance floor and go
Dialogue: 0,0:50:48.96,0:50:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,because you've watched it and now you've\Nlike practiced it mentally. Uh that's a
Dialogue: 0,0:50:55.28,0:51:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,very interesting phenomenal phenomena\Nand of course the mirroring can be uh
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.80,0:51:10.55,Default,,0,0,0,,positive or negative. So you can also\Nget negatively mirrored. Uh so you're
Dialogue: 0,0:51:10.55,0:51:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,mirroring you're watching behavior which\Nis not beneficial
Dialogue: 0,0:51:15.76,0:51:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,but your mind will direct you to do the\Nmost familiar thing. So mirroring means
Dialogue: 0,0:51:22.40,0:51:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,that your neurons are becoming familiar\Nwith the whole thing. So if you watch
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.68,0:51:33.68,Default,,0,0,0,,somebody shoot a game of billiards,\Nuh you can learn, you can become better
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.68,0:51:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,at it by merely watching. So if you keep\Nwatching uh somebody do, you know, two
